SUMMARY:Deadline: AWS Imagine Grant UK & Ireland 2026: Pathfinder Award (Fr
 ontier AI)
DESCRIPTION:UK & Ireland Pathfinder track of the 2026 AWS Imagine Grant. Fo
 r registered nonprofit charities with strong data practices\, in the plann
 ing phase of incorporating frontier AI (generative AI\, agentic AI\, auton
 omous systems) as a core workload during the grant term. Up to $100K cash 
 + $50K AWS credits\, plus AWS technical and training support. Round One cl
 oses 12 June 2026\; notifications 14 July\; Round Two open 10 August to 2 
 October 2026. Eligibility: registered nonprofit charities based in the UK 
 or Ireland. NOTE: this is a charities-only programme and is not open to in
 dividual artists\, researchers\, or for-profit studios.\n\nOrganisation: A
 mazon Web Services (AWS Imagine Grant Program)\nLocation: United Kingdom &
  Ireland (registered nonprofit charities only)\nAward: Up to $100\,000 USD
  unrestricted cash + up to $50\,000 USD in AWS Promotional Credits + AWS t
 echnical and training support\nDuration: Two-round process. Round One clos
 es 12 June 2026\; Round One notification 14 July 2026\; Round Two opens 10
  August 2026 and closes 2 October 2026.\n\nMore: https://aws.amazon.com/go
 vernment-education/nonprofits/aws-imagine-grant-program/aws-imagine-grant-
 uk/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://aws.amazon.com/government-education/nonprofits/aws-imagine-gran
 t-program/aws-imagine-grant-uk/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_
 medium=referral
LOCATION:United Kingdom & Ireland (registered nonprofit charities only)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:oxford-accelerator-fellowship-ethics-in-ai-2026-27@artificialnouveau.gi
 thub.io
DTSTAMP:20260724T115226Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260615
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260616
SUMMARY:Deadline: Oxford Institute for Ethics in AI: Accelerator Fellowship
  Programme 2026/27
DESCRIPTION:Accelerator Fellowship Programme at the University of Oxford's 
 Institute for Ethics in AI\, supporting impact-driven projects addressing 
 the urgent ethical challenges posed by artificial intelligence\, grounded 
 in philosophical inquiry\, academic independence and a collaborative ethos
 . 3-4 fellows recruited for the 2026/27 cohort. NOT FOR: early-stage\, pro
 of-of-concept\, or blue-skies-only proposals. PROJECTS MUST: be already on
  a clear path to creating meaningful impact\, with established or clearly 
 identified partnerships\, a well-defined delivery roadmap\, and clear indi
 cators of how impact will be achieved and measured. POTENTIAL IMPACT INCLU
 DES: policy or governance innovation in AI\; new professional-development 
 opportunities in the AI industry\; commercial or technical innovation in r
 esponsible AI\; strategic networks/alliances\; transformation of public di
 scourse on AI ethics. ELIGIBILITY: practising professionals and academics 
 from any discipline\, holding a continuing role within a university\, not-
 for-profit research organisation\, industry\, or who are otherwise profess
 ionally established and engaging with AI. Open worldwide\; proficiency in 
 English required. PhD applicants: 2+ peer-reviewed publications and a risi
 ng trajectory of research including at least one grant as PI or Co-I. Non-
 PhD applicants: 7+ years equivalent professional standing with advanced ex
 pertise\, original contributions\, peer/professional recognition\, and sig
 nificant impact. WHAT FELLOWS GET: GBP 2\,000/month stipend\; economy UK t
 ravel and visa costs covered\; intellectual engagement with Oxford researc
 hers\; visibility through seminars\, public discussions\, collaborative ev
 ents\; flexible self-directed structure (no formal supervision)\; inductio
 n meeting plus a one-day retreat. FORMAT: remote with short visits\, or up
  to 6 months in-person in Oxford (subject to UK immigration eligibility)\;
  in-person stays should align with university term dates. NOTE: this is NO
 T an employed position with the University. APPLY: (1) complete the online
  application form\; (2) email the three documents (Project Statement max 5
 00 words including impact pathways and any project-cost proposal\; Motivat
 ion Letter max 500 words\; CV max 2 pages) as PDFs to aiethicsafp@philosop
 hy.ox.ac.uk with subject line 'AFP Fellowship Application' and the naming 
 convention 'Surname_Name_Month_Year_AFP_filetype'. TIMELINE: applications 
 opened 25 May 2026\; deadline 15 June 2026 23:59 UK time (programme reserv
 es the right to close applications early). VISA: if needed\, allow 6 month
 s before intended visit\; 3 months otherwise.\n\nOrganisation: Institute f
 or Ethics in AI\, University of Oxford\nLocation: Remote with intermittent
  short visits to Oxford\, OR up to 6 months in-person in Oxford\, UK\nAwar
 d: Monthly stipend of GBP 2\,000 to support accommodation\, travel\, food 
 and living expenses. Economy airfare to and from the UK and any visa costs
  covered. Project-related costs (workshops\, seminars\, public exhibitions
 /events) considered case-by-case if a clear proposal and brief cost justif
 ication are included in the application. No application fee.\nDuration: 6 
 or 12 months. Earliest remote start: September 2026. In-person start dates
 : April 2027 or September 2027\n\nMore: https://afp.oxford-aiethics.ox.ac.
 uk/join?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://afp.oxford-aiethics.ox.ac.uk/join?utm_source=artificialnouveaug
 rantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Remote with intermittent short visits to Oxford\, OR up to 6 month
 s in-person in Oxford\, UK
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:govai-uk-winter-fellowship-2027-research-track@artificialnouveau.github
 .io
DTSTAMP:20260724T115226Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260712
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260713
SUMMARY:Deadline: GovAI UK Winter Fellowship 2027 - Research Track
DESCRIPTION:GovAI's UK Winter Fellowship (Research Track) is a three-month 
 in-person fellowship in London for researchers and policy professionals se
 eking to enter or advance careers in AI governance and policy. Fellows con
 duct independent research on a topic of their choice\, paired with a GovAI
  supervisor from the team or network\; the first two weeks are spent explo
 ring the AI governance landscape before a research proposal is finalised. 
 Research outputs may include a report\, white paper\, journal article\, op
 -ed\, or blog post targeted at an audience relevant to AI governance. Alon
 gside the project\, fellows attend expert Q&As\, weekly seminars\, skills 
 workshops\, work-in-progress meetings\, and social events\, and are encour
 aged to discuss follow-on career opportunities with GovAI's team and netwo
 rk. GovAI alumni have gone on to roles in US\, UK\, and EU government\; le
 ading AI companies (Anthropic\, DeepMind\, OpenAI)\; top think tanks (CSET
 \, RAND)\; and leading universities (Oxford\, Cambridge). AMOUNT: £12\,00
 0 salary for three months\, plus travel support to London and weekday lunc
 h. Visa sponsorship for a 3-month temporary work visa is available\; succe
 ssful visa applicants must remain in their country of application while th
 e visa is processed. ELIGIBILITY: open to a wide range of backgrounds (gov
 ernment\, academia\, industry\, civil society)\; no strict degree requirem
 ents\; relevant areas include public policy\, political science\, computer
  science\, economics\, biosecurity\, cybersecurity\, China studies\, and r
 isk management. Senior candidates who need accommodations should email fel
 lowships@governance.ai with subject line 'senior candidate winter fellowsh
 ip 2027' and a CV. SELECTION CRITERIA: quality and clarity of written work
 \, relevant expertise\, judgement in prioritising research directions\, an
 d team fit (intellectual honesty\, openness to feedback\, comfort with unc
 ertainty). APPLICATION PROCESS: (1) written application and automated abst
 ract reasoning assessment\; (2) paid remote work test (August 2026)\; (3) 
 remote interview and reference checks (September 2026)\; decisions communi
 cated October 2026. Deadline: 12 July 2026\, 23:59 BST.\n\nOrganisation: C
 entre for the Governance of AI (GovAI)\nLocation: London\, UK\; in-person\
 , full-time.\nAward: £12\,000 salary for the three-month term\, plus trav
 el support to London and weekday lunch provided. Visa sponsorship (3-month
  temporary work visa) available. No application fee.\nDuration: 3 months\,
  18 January to 9 April 2027.\n\nMore: https://www.governance.ai/post/winte
 r-fellowship-2027-research-track?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm
 _medium=referral
URL:https://www.governance.ai/post/winter-fellowship-2027-research-track?ut
 m_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:London\, UK\; in-person\, full-time.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:sound-image-2026-call-for-works-greenwich@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260724T115226Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260619
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260620
SUMMARY:Deadline: SOUND/IMAGE 2026: "Artistic Intelligence" - Call for Work
 s
DESCRIPTION:SOUND/IMAGE 2026 is the 11th edition of the University of Green
 wich festival exploring sound and image practice\, running 5-8 November 20
 26 in London. This year's theme is "Artistic Intelligence": a critical ref
 lection on creative choice\, agency\, and authenticity in the context of a
 lgorithmic and AI-mediated art making. The festival cites reference points
  from Vera Molnár\, Pauline Oliveros\, John Cage\, Iannis Xenakis\, Ryoji
  Ikeda\, and Refik Anadol. Special consideration is given to students\, ap
 prentices\, and emerging artists\; submissions are welcome from composers\
 , filmmakers\, artists\, performers\, and architects. CATEGORIES ACCEPTED:
  sound and music works\; audiovisual works\; talks\; artist statements\; w
 orkshops and practical demonstrations\; live performances\; installations.
  THEMATIC AREAS: embodied knowledge and lived experience in aesthetic judg
 ement\; creative choice vs chance encounters\; ownership\, authenticity\, 
 and AI co-creation\; human and algorithmic capability\; spatial and immers
 ive audio-visual forms\; interdisciplinary practice (CreaTech)\; practice 
 research. SUBMISSION RULES: works under 15 minutes in duration (installati
 ons exempt from duration limit)\; maximum three submissions per artist acr
 oss all categories\; artists must attend and present in person\; submit se
 parately for each submission via Microsoft CMT. FESTIVAL PASS: all accepte
 d artists must purchase a festival pass at a reduced rate of £25. Notific
 ations before end of July 2026. Deadline: 19 June 2026\, 23:59 UTC+1 (exte
 nded from 12 June). Submit at https://blogs.gre.ac.uk/sound-image/sound-im
 age-2026-call-for-works/.\n\nOrganisation: University of Greenwich\nLocati
 on: University of Greenwich\, London\, UK\; in-person attendance required.
 \nAward: No payment to artists. All accepted artists must purchase a festi
 val pass at a reduced rate of £25 (covers catering and technical support)
 .\nDuration: Festival runs 5-8 November 2026.\n\nMore: https://blogs.gre.a
 c.uk/sound-image/sound-image-2026-call-for-works/?utm_source=artificialnou
 veaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://blogs.gre.ac.uk/sound-image/sound-image-2026-call-for-works/?ut
 m_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:University of Greenwich\, London\, UK\; in-person attendance requi
 red.
END:VEVENT
END:VCALENDAR
